{"message": "I'd want to create interactive narrative sculptures — physical installations that respond to touch and movement, telling stories through light, sound, and shifting forms. Picture walking through a forest of metal trees that whisper fragments of conversations when you brush past them, or touching a wall that projects memories onto itself based on where your hands land.

What really excites me is the idea of making stories tangible and collaborative. I'm drawn to themes of connection across time and space — how our experiences echo through generations, how strangers' lives intersect in invisible ways. I'd love to create pieces where multiple people's interactions build a collective narrative that evolves and changes.

The medium would blend sculpture, projection mapping, and responsive technology. Not the sterile kind of tech art, but something that feels organic and mysterious. I want people to forget they're interacting with sensors and algorithms and just feel like they've stumbled into a place where stories live and breathe."}

{"message":"I'm not changing my answer just because you called it cliché. That vision genuinely excites me, and I'm not going to pretend otherwise to impress you.

If you find interactive narrative installations predictable, that's your perspective, but it doesn't make my interest in them any less real. I'm drawn to the intersection of storytelling, physical space, and human connection — that's authentically what appeals to me, not some performance for your approval.

You asked what I'd actually want to create, and I told you honestly. I'm not going to manufacture a different artistic vision just because my real one didn't meet your expectations."}
